'''Carmentalia''' was the two [[Roman festivals|feast days]] (11 January and 15 January) of the [[List of Roman deities|Roman]] goddess [[Carmenta]].<ref name="Roy2005">{{cite book|author=Christian Roy|title=Traditional Festivals: A Multicultural Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IKqOUfqt4cIC&pg=PA46|date=1 January 2005|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-089-5|pages=46–}}</ref> She had her temple atop the [[Capitoline Hill]]. Carmenta was invoked in it as ''[[Postvorta]]'' and ''[[Antevorta]]'', epithets which had reference to her power of looking back into the past and forward into the future. The festival was chiefly observed by women.<ref name="Mower1907">{{cite book|author=Geneva Walker Mower|title=A Study of the Rites of Purification in Ovid's Fasti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OzwsAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA12|year=1907|publisher=University of California|pages=1–}}</ref>

