{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}
[[File:Defense.gov News Photo 970404-N-0000N-001.jpg|thumb|right|''Kapitan Man'' on 4 April 1997]]
On 4 April 1997, a [[Canadian Armed Forces]] helicopter was allegedly [[lasers and aviation safety|illuminated by a laser]] while observing the Russian [[merchant ship]] and suspected [[spy ship|spy vessel]] ''[[Kapitan Man]]'', which was in the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]] in U.S. territorial waters near [[Port Angeles, Washington]]. The [[Canadian Air Force]] pilot and the [[U.S. Navy]] passenger, who was taking photographs of the ship, reportedly suffered eye pain and injuries consistent with laser exposure. However, subsequent investigations into the incident were unable to verify that any lasing had occurred.

==Background==
Responding to a request based on previous suspicious activity of the ''Kapitan Man'', the [[Canadian Forces]] dispatched a [[CH-124]] helicopter to fly by the ship and take photographs of it and its abnormal aerial [[antenna (radio)|antenna]] structure, which was indicative of a ship that could be conducting [[ELINT]] or [[SIGINT]] activities. The [[U.S. Coast Guard]] had previously confiscated submarine surveillance equipment from the ship in 1993.<ref name="AP 97" /> At the time of the incident, the ''Kapitan Man'' was {{convert|5|nmi|0}} north of [[Port Angeles, Washington]] i.e. inside U.S. territorial waters.<ref name="HASC 99" />

On board the aircraft were [[U.S. Navy]] Lieutenant Jack Daly and [[Canadian Forces]] pilot Captain Patrick Barnes. Lt. Daly was the Navy's [[foreign-intelligence]] [[liaison officer]] in [[Esquimalt, British Columbia]], heading a joint U.S.-Canadian helicopter-surveillance operation against Russian, Chinese, and other [[spy ship]]s operating in the Strait of Juan de Fuca, which separates the Canadian province of [[British Columbia]] from the U.S. state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]], and in [[Puget Sound]], the site of major U.S. [[nuclear weapon|nuclear]] [[ballistic missile submarine]] and [[aircraft carrier]] bases with the Royal Canadian Navy Pacific Fleet Headquarters in Esquimalt Harbour near Victoria, B.C.

==Laser damage==
While taking photographs of the ship and its [[bridge (ship)|bridge]], Lt. Daly suddenly experienced intense pain in his right eye as well as temporary blindness. After examination, it was concluded that Daly suffered direct [[laser]] burns to his right eye, as well as other vision problems and severe headaches.{{Citation needed |date=August 2014}} Daly testified that Capt. Barnes was also injured in a similar manner and was permanently grounded as a result of this incident, he has since lost all his [[pilot licensing and certification|flight qualifications]].<ref name="HASC 99"/> A United States Army Medical Research Department analysis indicated that the crew was most likely hit with a [[Nd:YAG laser]].{{Citation needed |date=August 2014}}

In February 1999, Daly testified before the U.S. House Armed Services Committee about his experience.<ref name="AP 97">{{cite news |title=Navy Officer Blames Russian Laser |url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1999/Navy-Officer-Blames-Russian-Laser/id-70804cac00b84d4533ff12067869b0cd |accessdate=27 May 2013 |newspaper=AP News Archive |date=12 February 1999}}</ref> He said that he and Capt. Barnes both had extreme sensitivity to sunlight and light sources. Driving at night became impossible as did watching movies or night ball games: "The only form of even momentary relief that either one of us can rely on is sitting in the dark with our eyes closed,  yet lately even that does not seem to help much."<ref name="HASC 99">{{cite web |title=Statement of Lt. Daly |url=http://www.fas.org/spp/starwars/congress/1999_h/99-02-11daly.htm |work=February 11, 1999 House Armed Services Committee transcript |publisher=Federation of American Scientists |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> In the same time period, he discussed his case on the ABC News program ''[[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|20/20]]'', saying "I've been in constant pain since the 4th of April '97, without a moment's relief."<ref>{{cite web|title=Fearsome Weapons of Future Wars |url=http://servv89pn0aj.sn.sourcedns.com/~gbpprorg/mil/herf/2020_transcript.txt |work=ABC News 20/20 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=27 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231051150/http://servv89pn0aj.sn.sourcedns.com/~gbpprorg/mil/herf/2020_transcript.txt |archivedate=31 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>

==''Kapitan Man'' search==
Shortly after the incident, [[U.S. Coast Guard]] teams were given two hours to search the vessel but did not locate a laser. Teams were not given full access to the ship, however, and the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] administration had warned the Russian government in advance the ship would be searched.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.papillonsartpalace.com/navyman.htm |title=Navy Man Clinton Hung Out To Dry Gets His Day in Court |publisher=Papillonsartpalace.com |accessdate=7 July 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803005723/http://www.papillonsartpalace.com/navyman.htm |archivedate=3 August 2010 |df= }}</ref>

==Lawsuit and Purple Heart request==

In October 2002, Daly sued the Russian [[Far East Shipping Company]] (FESCO), owner of the ''Kapitan Man'', in federal court. In his opening statement, Daly's lawyer laid out their side of the case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Statement |url=http://www.judicialwatch.org/cases/77/openstatement.htm |accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> The company's lawyer countered that there was no positive evidence of a laser on the ship. The jury deliberated for a day and ruled that the laser attack could not be linked to FESCO.  Daly's lawyer told the press that the case was hampered by U.S. government resistance and unfavorable rulings by the judge.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navy officer loses suit against Russians |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2002/oct/19/20021019-093035-6314r/ |accessdate=25 May 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=19 October 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Navy Man Loses Laser Lawsuit |url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/2002/Navy-Man-Loses-Laser-Lawsuit/id-7948823ff9caabd508ada72ecf49a4ff |accessdate=27 May 2013 |newspaper=AP News Archive |date=21 October 2002}}</ref>

In September 2004, the [[Chief of Naval Operations]] denied an Inspector General's recommendation that Daly be awarded the [[Purple Heart]] (for wounds sustained by opposing forces). Part of the CNO's rejection stated:

{{quote|In summary, even assuming that the injuries were indeed caused by a laser aimed from the Russian-flagged merchant vessel ''Kapitan Man'', there is no basis to declare that ship a hostile force or the incident a terrorist act.... [W]hile we regret any injuries Lt. Cmdr. Daly sustained while in service to his country, the facts of this case do not support an award of the Purple Heart.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navy turns down appeal for award |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2004/sep/23/20040923-114729-8717r/?page=all |accessdate=25 May 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=23 September 2004}}</ref>}}

==Clinical assessment==
{{Over-quotation |date=August 2014}}
The case was analyzed in the August 2004 ''[[Archives of Ophthalmology]]'' by medical laser researchers including Dr. Bruce Stuck, then Director of the U.S. Army Medical Research Detachment of the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research, responsible for the Army Medical Department's laser and radio frequency radiation biological effects research program.<ref>{{cite web |title=ICNERP Members' Biographical Information |url=http://www.icnirp.org/cv.htm |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref> Although the analysis of "Case 5" did not explicitly state Daly's name or the military nature of the ship photography, the case description is clearly that of the Strait of Juan de Fuca laser incident.

The researchers noted the photographer's (Daly's) case history:
{{quote|A retina specialist found 3 tiny (10- to 20-μm) [[Retinal pigment epithelium|RPE]] window defects in one eye on a [[Fluorescein angiography|fluorescein angiogram]] and ascribed them to laser injury. Findings from [[optical coherence tomography]] were normal. [[Amsler grid]] test results were highly variable, and the locations of grid abnormalities and RPE defects were inconsistent.... New RPE defects developed after the incident. The photographer had not been diagnosed previously as having reactive arthritis ([[Reiter syndrome]]), which can produce small RPE defects.... No evidence of laser injury was found in the years after the incident by 17 other ophthalmologists, including 5 neuro-ophthalmalogists and 8 retina specialists. A trial was held five years after the incident in which the retina specialist who made the initial diagnosis steadfastly maintained all the photographer's symptoms were due to retinal laser injury. A jury ruled against the photographer's claim for damages against the ship's owner.}}

The Analysis section of the article stated:
{{quote|A costly, time-consuming chain of events was precipitated by the initial retina specialist's (1) failure to attach significance to an association between the photographer's symptoms and his complex past medical history, (2) quick diagnosis of a laser injury, (3) subsequent attribution of the photographer's growing list of pains and visual complaints to a laser injury, and (4) diagnosis of laser exposure in the photographer's associate based on symptoms in the absence of retinal or angiographic abnormalities. As noted previously herein, the few tiny RPE defects on which the initial diagnosis was based are common. Even if these defects were due to threshold laser effects, they could not have caused the photographer's reported problems or millions of patients would be afflicted with similar problems after routine retinal laser surgery.… The patient had real complaints, but they were caused by preexisting [[Autoimmune disease|autoimmune problems]] rather than by laser injury.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Mainster |first=Martin |author2=Stuck, Bruce |author3=Brown, Jeremiah |title=Assessment of Alleged Retinal Laser Injuries |journal=Arch Ophthalmol |date=August 2004  |volume=2122 |pages=1210–1217 |doi=10.1001/archopht.122.8.1210 |url=http://archopht.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=416518 |accessdate=24 May 2013}}</ref>}}

