The '''Tanjung Priok massacre''' was an incident that occurred in the port area of [[Tanjung Priok]], [[North Jakarta]], Indonesia in 1984. Government reports give a total of 24 killed and 54 injured, while survivors report over a hundred killed.

==Background==
On 10 September 1984, Sergeant Hermanu,<ref>http://print.kompas.com/baca/2015/06/26/Sudah-Saling-Memaafkan</ref> a member of the Community Advisory Non-Commissioned Officer  ({{lang|id|Bintara Pembina Desa}}) arrived at As Saadah Mosque in [[Tanjung Priok]], North Jakarta, and told the caretaker, Amir Biki, to remove brochures and banners critical of the government.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}} Biki refused this demand, upon which point Hermanu removed them himself; to do so, he reportedly entered the prayer area of the mosque without removing his shoes (a serious violation of mosque etiquette).{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}}{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} In response, local residents, led by mosque caretakers Syarifuddin Rambe and Sofwan Sulaeman, burned his motorcycle and attacked Hermanu while he was talking with another officer.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}}{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} The two then arrested Rambe and Sulaeman, as well as another caretaker, Achmad Sahi, and an unemployed man named Muhamad Noor.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}}{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}}{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, Victims 'may not}}

==Incident==
Two days after the arrest, Islamic cleric Abdul Qodir Jaelani gave a sermon against [[Pancasila (politics)|Pancasila]] at As Saadah mosque.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} Afterwards, Biki led a protest to the District Military Command office for North Jakarta, where the four prisoners were being held.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}}{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} Along the way, the group's numbers swelled, with estimates ranging between 1,500 and several thousand.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}}{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} Also during the trip, nine members of a Muslim [[Chinese Indonesian]] family headed by Tan Kioe Liem were killed by the protestors.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2000, FPI members attacks}}{{sfn|Setiono|2008|p=1057}} The family's store, a pharmacy, was burned to the ground.{{sfn|Setiono|2008|p=1057}}

Once at the military command, the group unsuccessfully demanded the release of the prisoners.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}} At roughly 11 p.m. [[Time in Indonesia|local time]] (UTC+7), the protestors surrounded the military command.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} Military personnel from the 6th Air Defence Artillery Battalion opened fire on the protestors.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=17}}{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, Victims report to UN}} Around midnight, eyewitnesses saw military commander of Jakarta [[Try Sutrisno]] and Chief of the Armed Forces [[Leonardus Benjamin Moerdani]] supervising the removal of the victims; the corpses were loaded into military trucks and buried in unmarked graves, while the wounded were sent to Gatot Soebroto Military Hospital.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=18}}

==Aftermath==
After the riots, the military reported that they had been triggered by a man in a fake military uniform who distributed anti-government pamphlets along with 12 other accomplices; it reported having the man in custody.{{sfn|The New York Times 1984, Around the World;}} General [[Hartono Rekso Dharsono]] was arrested for allegedly inciting the riots.{{sfn|Erlanger 1990, Jakarta Journal; Echoes}}  After a four-month trial, he was convicted; he was eventually released in September 1990, after serving five-years jail time.{{sfn|Erlanger 1990, Jakarta Journal; Echoes}}

After the riots, at least 169 civilians were allegedly held without warrant.{{sfn|Taufiqurrahman 2004, I was tortured}} Some were reportedly tortured.{{sfn|Taufiqurrahman 2004, I was tortured}} The leaders were arrested and tried for subversion, then given long sentences when convicted.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} Others, including as Amir Biki, were among those killed.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=18}}

Initial reports suggested 20 dead.{{sfn|The New York Times 1984, Around the World;}} Current official records give a total of 24 killed and 54 injured (including the military), while survivors report over a hundred killed.{{sfn|Khalik 2008, Govt slammed for human}} Tanjung Priok residents estimate a total of 400 killed or missing, while other reports suggest up to 700 victims.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=18}}{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, Victims report to UN}}

==Investigation==
With the influx of human rights movements after the [[fall of Suharto]] in 1998, several groups were created to advocate for the rights of the victims, including the {{nowrap|12 September}} 1984 Foundation, the National Solidarity for the 1984 Tanjung Priok Incident ({{lang|id|Solidaritas Nastional untuk Peristiwa Tanjung Priok 1984}}), and the Extended Family for Victims of the Tanjung Priok Incident ({{lang|id|Keluarga Besar Korban Peristiwa Tanjung Priok}}; founded by Biki's widow Dewi Wardah and son Beni).{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=18}} These groups pushed for the [[People's Representative Council]] (DPR) and [[National Commission on Human Rights (Indonesia)|National Commission on Human Rights]] (Komnas HAM) to further investigate the massacre; inside the DPR, representatives A.W. Fatwa and Abdul Qodir Jaelani, both previously arrested after the massacre, pressed for further investigation.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=20}} In 1999, Komnas HAM agreed to investigate the incident, forming the Commission for the Investigation and Examination of Human Rights Violations in Tanjung Priok (KP3T).{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=20}}

The KP3T consisted mainly of political figures from the [[New Order (Indonesia)|previous regime]], including former prosecutor general Djoko Sugianto.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=21}} The resulting report, released in early June 2000, found that there had been no systematic massacre in the incident.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=21}} This was not well received by the general public. On 23 June 2000, approximately 300 members of the [[Islamic Defenders Front]] (FPI) attacked the headquarters of Komnas HAM while dressed in white [[Islamic clothing]] and green scarves.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2000, FPI members attacks}} They broke windows with stones and [[rattan]] sticks, outnumbering and overwhelming the security forces.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2000, FPI members attacks}} The FPI was upset at the commission's report on the massacre and perceived collusion with the military, arguing that it had ignored actions by the military; it insisted that the commission be abolished.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2000, FPI members attacks}} Meanwhile, [[List of ministers of law and human rights of Indonesia|Minister of Law and Human Rights]] [[Yusril Ihza Mahendra]] wrote that Komnas HAM had seemingly applied double standards when investigating the issue; he said that they seemed more reluctant to investigate the Tanjung Priok incident then they had been in investigating the [[1999 East Timorese crisis]].{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=21}} [[Crescent Star Party (Indonesia)|Crescent Star Party]] leader Ahmad Sumargono called the verdict a disappointment to Muslims everywhere.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=21}}

In October 2000, Komnas HAM released another report indicating that 23 individuals, including Sutrisno and Moerdani, should be investigated for their involvement; it called for an ''[[ad hoc]]'' tribunal to look into the matter further.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=21}} With President [[Abdurrahman Wahid]] calling for further investigation and the impending tribunal, several military officials made contracts of forgiveness (''islah'') with victims' families; although the islah did not contain admissions of guilt, it did provide for victims to receive a lump sum of [[Indonesian Rupiah|Rp.]] 1.5-2 million (US$200–250).{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=22}} The first islah covered 86 families, as represented by Rambe, while the second covered Biki's family; by 1 March 2001 a number of islah had been made.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=22}} As a result of the islah, several victims or their families, suggested to investigator M.A. Rachman that charges be dropped.{{sfn|Junge|2008|p=23}} However, investigation continued, wrapping up in July 2003.{{sfn|KontraS, Massacre of Tanjung Priok}}

Under international pressure, in 2003 the DPR approved the use of the 2000 human rights law to bring perpetrators of the massacre to trial for crimes against humanity;{{sfn|Khalik 2008, Govt slammed for human}}{{sfn|Saraswati 2003, Tanjung Priok rights}} the trial began in September of that year.{{sfn|KontraS, Massacre of Tanjung Priok}} Those brought to trial included Colonel Sutrisno Mascung, leader of Platoon II of the Air Defense Artillery Battalion at the time, and 13 subordinates.{{sfn|Saraswati 2003, Tanjung Priok rights}} Higher-ranking officials from the time, including military commander of Jakarta [[Try Sutrisno]] and Chief of the Armed Forces [[Leonardus Benjamin Moerdani]], were exempted from prosecution, as were former President [[Suharto]] and former Minister of Justice [[Ismail Saleh]].{{sfn|Saraswati 2003, Tanjung Priok rights}}{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2003, Soeharto blamed}} The prosecution was led by Widodo Supriyadi, and Deputy Speaker of the DPR A.M. Fatwa served as a witness for the prosecution.{{sfn|Taufiqurrahman 2004, I was tortured}}{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2003, Court urged to pursue}} Several officers prosecuted were convicted, while Sriyanto and Pranowo were acquitted.{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}} In 2004 the Prosecutor General's office filed an appeal against the acquittals of Sriyanto and Pranowo, but were refused.{{sfn|Khalik 2008, Govt slammed for human}} The convictions were later overturned by the [[Supreme Court of Indonesia]].{{sfn|Haryanto 2010, Death Toll From 1984 Massacre}}

After the trial it came under fire from human rights groups; German author Fabian Junge argued that "prosecutors deliberately ignored substantial evidence while scare-tactics and bribery were rampant outside court".{{sfn|Khalik 2008, Govt slammed for human}} Approaching the 25th anniversary of the massacre, the victims, aided by the Human Rights Working Group and the Commission for Missing Persons and Victims of Violence, sent a letter to [[United Nations Special Rapporteur|UN Special Rapporteur]] on the Independence of Judges and Lawyers Gabriela Carina Knaul de Albuquerque e Silva imploring her to intervene in the case;{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, Victims report to UN}} the survivors have also requested compensation in the amount of Rp1.015 billion (US$130,000) from the government for their "pain and loss".{{sfn|KontraS, Massacre of Tanjung Priok}}{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, Victims 'may not}} Although victims and their representatives have asked President [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] to further investigate the issue, {{as of|2011|lc=y}} the case has not come to closure.{{sfn|KontraS, Massacre of Tanjung Priok}}

